Central to the overall circulation pattern is the polar vortex, a fast‑moving wind system that surrounds both poles at the interface of the troposphere and stratosphere. Recent work by Yifeng Peng and colleagues shows that the amount of aerosols reaching the poles depends strongly on the location and timing of when they are injected into the atmosphere (Geophys. Res. Lett. 52, e2025GL116525; 2025). Using satellite data and climate model simulations, the authors find that aerosols released in the tropics can reach the atmosphere above Antarctica when the polar vortex is weak. In contrast, the movement of aerosols from the mid‑latitudes to the poles depends more on the season in which they enter the atmosphere than on wind patterns.Stratospheric circulation and seasonal dynamics are closely tied to the quasi‑biennial oscillation — a regular 14‑month shift in equatorial winds between easterly and westerly directions — Jinhwa Shin and colleagues now suggest (Sci. Adv. 11, eadv1172; 2025). This oscillation alters stratospheric airflow, creating intermittent periods when transport of material to Antarctica is reduced. Between 1945 and 1980, atmospheric nuclear weapons tests released Plutonium-239-rich debris into the stratosphere, which later settled as fallout, forming a useful radioactive tracer. By analysing sub-annual resolution ice core records from Greenland and Antarctica, the authors reconstructed how this material travelled from nuclear test sites to the polar regions. The timing of these tests, like those conducted by the USA in the Marshall Islands, strongly influenced how their fallout spread, even though the explosions had similar yields and locations. The Ivy Mike test, conducted in November 1952, generated fallout that westerly winds confined mainly to the Northern Hemisphere. By contrast, the Castle Bravo test in March 1954 coincided with an easterly wind phase, enabling dispersal across both hemispheres.



